WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.539 --> 00:00:02.659
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:02.659 --> 00:00:06.020
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:06.020 --> 00:00:09.670
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:09.670 --> 00:00:14.230
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:14.230 --> 00:00:15.230
of videos.

00:00:15.230 --> 00:00:17.150
Thanks for your help.

00:00:17.150 --> 00:00:21.220
This lab will, once again, be different than
most of the labs in this course.

00:00:21.220 --> 00:00:27.110
Instead of configuring network devices, we
will download a free Type 2 hypervisor, Oracle

00:00:27.110 --> 00:00:31.480
VirtualBox, and then run a Linux virtual machine
on it.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:35.620
First up, let me say that this lab is not
necessary for the CCNA.

00:00:35.620 --> 00:00:39.790
For the CCNA exam you should know the basics
of virtualization I showed you in the lecture

00:00:39.790 --> 00:00:43.550
video, but you don’t have to know how to
set up a virtual machine.

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:48.100
So, why am I including this lab in the course
if it’s not necessary?

00:00:48.100 --> 00:00:49.260
There are three main reasons.

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:53.900
First, I think getting hands-on experience
will help you understand some of the concepts

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:55.460
you have learned.

00:00:55.460 --> 00:01:01.330
In this case, you’ll see how a type 2 hypervisor,
VirtualBox, runs on top of a host OS, windows

00:01:01.330 --> 00:01:02.899
in my case.

00:01:02.899 --> 00:01:07.940
And then you’ll see how a guest OS, Ubuntu
in this case, runs on top of the hypervisor.

00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:13.750
The second reason is that it’s actually
quite simple to set up a VM on a Type 2 hypervisor,

00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:19.010
so I want to show you that you can easily
do it without being a virtualization specialist.

00:01:19.010 --> 00:01:23.010
And the third reason is that it’s a good
idea to have a type 2 hypervisor, whether

00:01:23.010 --> 00:01:28.799
that’s virtualbox or another one such as
VMware workstation, for your future studies.

00:01:28.799 --> 00:01:35.600
For example, when I use GNS3 to run virtual
Cisco routers and switches, I run a GNS3 VM

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:38.900
in a type 2 hypervisor, VMware workstation.

00:01:38.900 --> 00:01:43.560
However, if for any reason you are unable
to complete this lab, for example if your

00:01:43.560 --> 00:01:48.800
PC doesn’t have sufficient specifications
to run a VM, don’t worry about it.

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:53.350
Just watch the video, and then continue to
the next part of the course.

00:01:53.350 --> 00:01:55.330
Okay let’s get right into it.

00:01:55.330 --> 00:02:01.890
To get VirtualBox, go to virtualbox.org and
click here where it says download virtualbox.

00:02:01.890 --> 00:02:07.220
Now, throughout this video I am going to assume
that you are using a Windows PC.

00:02:07.220 --> 00:02:11.480
Of course, I’m sure some of your use macOS
and some of you run Linux.

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:15.549
In that case, you should download the appropriate
version of VirtualBox.

00:02:15.549 --> 00:02:22.120
I will be downloading VirtualBox for Windows,
so I will click here, windows hosts.

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:31.769
VirtualBox will be downloaded, so let’s
open it and install it.

00:02:31.769 --> 00:02:37.931
I will use the default settings so let’s
just click next, and next, and next, click

00:02:37.931 --> 00:02:39.620
YES here, and click install.

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:41.169
Allow it to make changes, and then virtualbox
will be installed.

00:02:41.169 --> 00:02:45.379
It’s not a very long installation, but I
will cut the video here and return when it

00:02:45.379 --> 00:02:47.469
has finished.

00:02:47.469 --> 00:02:53.900
Okay the installation has finished so I will
click on Finish and open virtualbox.

00:02:53.900 --> 00:02:55.019
Here is virtual box.

00:02:55.019 --> 00:02:59.019
Now, to add a Linux VM we first need to download
Linux.

00:02:59.019 --> 00:03:03.959
Now, Linux isn’t actually an operating system,
it’s a family of operating systems that

00:03:03.959 --> 00:03:05.790
use the Linux kernel.

00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:10.809
Each operating system is often called a linux
distribution, or distro.

00:03:10.809 --> 00:03:13.920
For this video I’ve decided to use the Ubuntu
distro.

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:22.139
So, go to Ubuntu.com, click on download, and
click on the LTS, long term support, version.

00:03:22.139 --> 00:03:29.799
This is a fairly large file so I downloaded
it beforehand.

00:03:29.799 --> 00:03:38.870
So let’s return to virtualbox, and I’ll
click on New here to add a new VM.

00:03:38.870 --> 00:03:40.129
First we can set a name.

00:03:40.129 --> 00:03:46.859
I’ll name it Ubuntu 20.04, since that’s
the version of Ubuntu I downloaded.

00:03:46.859 --> 00:03:52.400
Notice that it automatically selected the
type, Linux, and version, Ubuntu, when I entered

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:53.400
the name.

00:03:53.400 --> 00:03:55.470
So, I’ll click next.

00:03:55.470 --> 00:04:00.379
Now we have to select how much memory to allocate
to the VM.

00:04:00.379 --> 00:04:05.849
My PC has 16 gigs, and the recommendation
for this Ubuntu VM is 1 gig.

00:04:05.849 --> 00:04:10.129
I want to keep this video as simple as possible
so I’ll leave it at 1, but if I actually

00:04:10.129 --> 00:04:13.589
wanted to use this VM I’d probably assign
it a bit more than that.

00:04:13.589 --> 00:04:16.850
Okay, I’ll click on next.

00:04:16.850 --> 00:04:21.570
Now the hard disk, I’ll click on ‘create’
to create a virtual hard disk for this VM

00:04:21.570 --> 00:04:22.570
to use.

00:04:22.570 --> 00:04:27.220
I’ll use the default hard disk file type,
so I’ll click next.

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:32.500
You can then select a dynamically allocated
or fixed size hard disk.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:37.020
You can read the difference here, but I’ll
stick with the default and click next.

00:04:37.020 --> 00:04:41.680
Now the size, I’ll leave it at the default
10 gigs and click create.

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:47.280
Okay, the VM has been created but there is
one more important step.

00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:51.280
Click on settings here to edit this VM.

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:55.620
Then storage, and click on this empty disk
here.

00:04:55.620 --> 00:05:00.880
Basically, we are going to insert an Ubuntu
disk into this virtual computer, so that we

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:03.720
can install the Ubuntu OS when it boots up.

00:05:03.720 --> 00:05:10.280
So, click on the blue disk here on the right,
click choose a disk file, and then select

00:05:10.280 --> 00:05:13.860
the ubuntu .iso file you just downloaded.

00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:16.840
Now I’ll click OK.

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:24.100
Okay, we are ready to boot the VM, so I’ll
click on start.

00:05:24.100 --> 00:05:30.520
The VM will boot up, and we will go through
the Ubuntu installation process.

00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:33.800
This will take some time so I will cut the
video whenever we have to wait for something

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:35.940
to load or install.

00:05:35.940 --> 00:05:39.580
Okay, we are greeted with the Ubuntu installation
wizard.

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:42.920
I’ll click on install ubuntu.

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:51.330
I’ll click on continue to use the US english
keyboard layout.

00:05:51.330 --> 00:05:56.740
Just to speed up the installation, here I’ll
click on minimal installation and disable

00:05:56.740 --> 00:05:59.810
the ‘download updates while installing ubuntu’
option.

00:05:59.810 --> 00:06:03.920
I won’t actually be using this VM, so this
is fine for me.

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:06.090
Now I’ll click continue.

00:06:06.090 --> 00:06:10.890
Here it says the computer currently has no
detected operating systems, which is expected,

00:06:10.890 --> 00:06:16.150
so I’ll leave this selected to erase the
disk and install Ubuntu, and click install

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:19.400
now.

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:21.480
And click continue here.

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:29.870
I’m in Japan so I’ll leave this as is
and click continue.

00:06:29.870 --> 00:06:33.080
Finally we have to register our information
and a user.

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:41.250
I’ll enter my name and username, and a password,
I’ll just make it cisco even though that’s

00:06:41.250 --> 00:06:42.740
a weak password.

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:45.600
And then click on continue.

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:49.810
Okay, now Ubuntu will be installed.

00:06:49.810 --> 00:06:53.680
This can take some time so I will once again
cut the video here until it’s finished.

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:57.163
After the installation is complete you will
be asked to restart the VM, and when you see

00:06:57.163 --> 00:06:58.163
this screen just press enter.

00:06:58.163 --> 00:06:59.740
And now our Ubuntu is up and running.

00:06:59.740 --> 00:07:05.870
So, I have Windows running on top of my PC
hardware, virtual box running on top of Windows,

00:07:05.870 --> 00:07:08.550
and Ubuntu running on top of virtual box.

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:10.490
I’ll end the lab here.

00:07:10.490 --> 00:07:13.760
If you don’t plan to use this VM you can
simply delete it.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:18.080
But you could also keep it and use the VM
to get familiar with Linux, which is a valuable

00:07:18.080 --> 00:07:20.310
skill for anyone in IT.

00:07:20.310 --> 00:07:21.530
But that’s up to you.

00:07:21.530 --> 00:07:27.500
So, in this lab we installed a type 2 hypervisor,
oracle virtualbox, and then installed a VM

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:28.500
on top of it.

00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:32.380
That’s all for this lab.

